.TH DST 1 dst\-VERSION
.SH NAME
dst \- dynamic suckless terminal
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dst
.RB [ \-aiv ]
.RB [ \-c
.IR class ]
.RB [ \-f
.IR font ]
.RB [ \-g
.IR geometry ]
.RB [ \-n
.IR name ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR iofile ]
.RB [ \-T
.IR title ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR title ]
.RB [ \-l
.IR line ]
.RB [ \-w
.IR windowid ]
.RB [[ \-e ]
.IR command
.RI [ arguments ...]]
.PP
.B dst
.RB [ \-aiv ]
.RB [ \-c
.IR class ]
.RB [ \-f
.IR font ]
.RB [ \-g
.IR geometry ]
.RB [ \-n
.IR name ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR iofile ]
.RB [ \-T
.IR title ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR title ]
.RB [ \-w
.IR windowid ]
.RB \-l
.IR line
.RI [ stty_args ...]
.PP
.B dst
.B \-\-rebuild
.PP
.B dst
.B \-\-install
.PP
.B dst
.B \-\-edit
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dst
is a fork of st, the suckless simple terminal. It keeps st's minimalism but
reads its settings at startup from a runtime configuration file
.RI ( ~/.config/dst/config )
instead of requiring a recompile, and it can apply upstream st patches
declaratively. See
.B CONFIGURATION
below.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-a
disable alternate screens in terminal
.TP
.BI \-c " class"
defines the window class (default $TERM).
.TP
.BI \-f " font"
defines the
.I font
to use when st is run.
.TP
.BI \-g " geometry"
defines the X11 geometry string.
The form is [=][<cols>{xX}<rows>][{+-}<xoffset>{+-}<yoffset>]. See
.BR XParseGeometry (3)
for further details.
.TP
.B \-i
will fixate the position given with the -g option.
.TP
.BI \-n " name"
defines the window instance name (default $TERM).
.TP
.BI \-o " iofile"
writes all the I/O to
.I iofile.
This feature is useful when recording st sessions. A value of "-" means
standard output.
.TP
.BI \-T " title"
defines the window title (default 'dst').
.TP
.BI \-t " title"
defines the window title (default 'dst').
.TP
.BI \-w " windowid"
embeds st within the window identified by
.I windowid
.TP
.BI \-l " line"
use a tty
.I line
instead of a pseudo terminal.
.I line
should be a (pseudo-)serial device (e.g. /dev/ttyS0 on Linux for serial port
0).
When this flag is given
remaining arguments are used as flags for
.BR stty(1).
By default st initializes the serial line to 8 bits, no parity, 1 stop bit
and a 38400 baud rate. The speed is set by appending it as last argument
(e.g. 'st -l /dev/ttyS0 115200'). Arguments before the last one are
.BR stty(1)
flags. If you want to set odd parity on 115200 baud use for example 'st -l
/dev/ttyS0 parenb parodd 115200'. Set the number of bits by using for
example 'st -l /dev/ttyS0 cs7 115200'. See
.BR stty(1)
for more arguments and cases.
.TP
.B \-v
prints version information to stderr, then exits.
.TP
.B \-\-rebuild
rebuilds the
.B dst
binary from a pristine source tree with the
.B include
patches listed in the config file applied, then installs it. Does not start a
terminal. See
.B CONFIGURATION
and
.BR REBUILDING .
.TP
.B \-\-install
creates a default config file at
.I ~/.config/dst/config
if none exists, then installs the
.B dst
binary under
.IR /usr/local/bin .
Falls back to
.I ~/.local/bin
on permission errors.
.TP
.B \-\-edit
opens the config file
.RI ( ~/.config/dst/config )
in
.BR $EDITOR ,
or
.B vi
if unset. Creates a default config if none exists.
.TP
.BI \-e " command " [ " arguments " "... ]"
st executes
.I command
instead of the shell.  If this is used it
.B must be the last option
on the command line, as in xterm / rxvt.
This option is only intended for compatibility,
and all the remaining arguments are used as a command
even without it.
.SH SHORTCUTS
.TP
.B Break
Send a break in the serial line.
Break key is obtained in PC keyboards
pressing at the same time control and pause.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Print Screen
Toggle if st should print to the
.I iofile.
.TP
.B Shift-Print Screen
Print the full screen to the
.I iofile.
.TP
.B Print Screen
Print the selection to the
.I iofile.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-Page Up
Increase font size.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-Page Down
Decrease font size.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-Home
Reset to default font size.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-y
Paste from primary selection (middle mouse button).
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-c
Copy the selected text to the clipboard selection.
.TP
.B Ctrl-Shift-v
Paste from the clipboard selection.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.B dst
reads
.I ~/.config/dst/config
(or
.IR $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/dst/config )
at startup. It is a line-oriented file: one directive per line, words
separated by whitespace, a leading
.B #
marks a comment line, and
.B set $name value
defines a variable that is substituted as
.B $name
on later lines. Recognised directives set the font, colors
.RB ( color0 .. color15 ,
.BR foreground ,
.BR background ,
.BR cursor ),
and assorted appearance and behaviour values
.RB ( borderpx ,
.BR tabspaces ,
.BR cursorshape ,
and others). Unknown or malformed lines are reported on stderr with a line
number and skipped. A missing file leaves the compiled-in defaults in place.
Changing a setting takes effect on the next launch \(em no recompile.
.PP
A sample configuration listing every directive is installed as
.IR config.sample .
.SH REBUILDING
Lines of the form
.B include
.I url
name an st patch (a unified diff). They are ignored on a normal launch and are
consumed only by
.BR "dst \-\-rebuild" ,
which copies a pristine source tree, applies each patch in order with
.BR patch (1),
rebuilds with the system toolchain, and installs the result only if the build
succeeds. Remove an
.B include
line and rebuild to drop that patch.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/dst/config
Runtime configuration and patch list read at startup and by \-\-rebuild.
.TP
.I ~/.cache/dst
Pristine source, fetched patches, and the temporary build tree used by
\-\-rebuild.
